00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.760
[Instructor] When we look at communities

00:00:01.760 --> 00:00:03.940
of organisms, an interesting
question to think

00:00:03.940 --> 00:00:06.790
about is how diverse
are those communities?

00:00:06.790 --> 00:00:09.570
And here I have two example communities

00:00:09.570 --> 00:00:12.090
and each of them is made
up of species of circles.

00:00:12.090 --> 00:00:14.240
Each species is represented
by a different color.

00:00:14.240 --> 00:00:15.370
And so pause this video.

00:00:15.370 --> 00:00:17.120
Intuitively, which of these communities

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:19.143
would you think to be more diverse?

00:00:20.470 --> 00:00:22.210
Well, if you look a community number one

00:00:22.210 --> 00:00:23.800
you see that it has two different colors

00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:25.680
of circles, or we could view that as two

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:27.960
different species, while
community number two

00:00:27.960 --> 00:00:29.500
has four different species.

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:31.110
So intuitively we would say that community

00:00:31.110 --> 00:00:33.400
number two is more diverse.

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:36.820
But how could we actually
quantify these things?

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:39.070
Well, to help us do that biologists

00:00:39.070 --> 00:00:41.050
have developed a tool, which is known

00:00:41.050 --> 00:00:44.140
as Simpson's Index of Diversity.

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:46.480
And so it's gonna be a number between zero

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:49.620
and one where one is a,
you could say a very,

00:00:49.620 --> 00:00:52.450
very diverse community and
zero'd be not diverse at all.

00:00:52.450 --> 00:00:54.270
And so let me write this down.

00:00:54.270 --> 00:00:58.000
So the index is going to be,
this is gonna be the index

00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:01.273
of diversity.

00:01:03.250 --> 00:01:07.380
And then capital N is
going to be the total

00:01:07.380 --> 00:01:09.810
population in that community,
so the total number

00:01:09.810 --> 00:01:12.160
of individuals of all species.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:17.160
So number of all individuals, individuals.

00:01:20.130 --> 00:01:24.940
And then n sub i is going
to be the number of,

00:01:24.940 --> 00:01:27.560
we could view that as the ith species.

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:32.560
So number of individuals,
viduals, in ith species

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:39.600
where i I'm saying, you
know, here there's two

00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:41.460
species so that'd be the first species

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:42.510
and they're the second species.

00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:44.510
So i would be one and then i would be two.

00:01:44.510 --> 00:01:46.240
Here there's four, so you would have it

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:47.970
the number of individuals
for the first, second,

00:01:47.970 --> 00:01:48.803
third, or fourth.

00:01:48.803 --> 00:01:50.320
So how do you put all of
these numbers together

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:52.360
to get the index of diversity?

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:55.000
Well, we would get this formula.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:56.630
And we're gonna apply it a few times

00:01:56.630 --> 00:01:57.930
to see why it makes sense.

00:01:57.930 --> 00:02:00.460
So Simpson's Index of
Diversity is gonna be equal

00:02:00.460 --> 00:02:05.460
to one minus the sum of
the product of n sub i

00:02:05.670 --> 00:02:10.670
times n sub i minus one, all of that over

00:02:10.970 --> 00:02:14.620
capital N times capital N minus one.

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:16.860
Now to see why this makes
sense, let's calculate

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:21.720
Simpson's Index of Diversity
for each of these communities.

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:24.340
So for community number
one, won't you let me

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:27.260
